6 A BILL
7 TO BE ENTITLED
8 AN ACT
9
10 Relating to the Alabama Sunset Law; to continue the
11 existence and functioning of the Alabama Sickle Cell Oversight
12 and Regulatory Commission until October 1, 2030, with certain
13 modifications; to amend Sections 22-10B-1 and 22-10B-2, Code
14 of Alabama 1975, to place the commission as a division within
15 the Alabama Department of Public Health; to require the
16 department to provide all necessary administrative services
17 for the commission; to authorize the department to provide for
18 an executive director and outside experts for the commission;
19 to transfer all property of the commission to the department;
20 and to change board members from being appointed subject to
21 confirmation by the Senate to serving upon appointment unless
22 and until rejected by the Senate.
23 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
24 Section 1. Pursuant to the Alabama Sunset Law, the
25 Sunset Committee recommends the continuance of the Alabama
26 Sickle Cell Oversight and Regulatory Commission until October
27 1, 2030, with additional recommendation for statutory change
28 as set out in Section 3.
Page 1

as set out in Section 3.
SB128 Engrossed
29 Section 2. The existence and functioning of the Alabama
30 Sickle Cell Oversight and Regulatory Commission, created and
31 functioning pursuant to Sections 22-10B-1 to 22-10B-7,
32 inclusive, Code of Alabama 1975, is continued until October 1,
33 2030, and those code sections are expressly preserved.
34 Section 3. Section 22-10B-1 and 22-10B-2, Code of
35 Alabama 1975, are amended to read as follows:
36 "§22-10B-1
37 (a) There is created and, beginning on October 1, 2026,
38 established as a division within the Alabama Department of
39 Public Health, the Alabama Sickle Cell Oversight and
40 Regulatory Commission.
41 (b) The department shall provide to the commission all
42 administrative services necessary for the commission to carry
43 out its duties, including:
44 (1) Financial services;
45 (2) Legal services;
46 (3) Dedicated office space;
47 (4) Administrative staff, who are shared with or
48 dedicated solely to the commission, and other personnel as
49 necessary for the efficient operation of the commission;
50 (5) Information technology services, including website
51 maintenance and dedicated phone lines and email addresses for
52 commission members and staff; and
53 (6) Necessary office furniture and supplies.
54 (c)(1) Any contract or binding agreement for
55 administrative services executed by the commission before the
56 effective date of this act shall continue in effect until
Page 2

effective date of this act shall continue in effect until
SB128 Engrossed
57 expiration as provided by its terms. After expiration, the
58 department shall assume all administrative services provided
59 by subsection (b).
60 (2) The commission may enter into a contract or other
61 agreement for the provision of administrative services so long
62 as the agreement terminates on or before October 1, 2026.
63 (d) When necessary, the department may retain the
64 services of outside experts, including an executive director,
65 accountants, attorneys, and consultants using funds
66 appropriated for use by the commission on behalf of the
67 commission.
68 (e) On October 1, 2026, all real and personal property
69 and all other effects of the commission shall transfer to the
70 department."
71 "§22-10B-2
72 (a) The commission shall consist of the following
73 members:
74 (1) Two members shall be appointed by the Governor.
75 (2) One member shall be appointed by the University of
76 South Alabama Comprehensive Sickle Cell Center.
77 (3) One member shall be appointed by the University of
78 Alabama-Birmingham Alabama at Birmingham.
79 (4) One member shall be appointed by the Children's
80 Hospital of Birmingham Alabama.
81 (5) Each of the seven chapters of the Sickle Cell
82 Disease Association of America-Alabama Chapter, Incorporated,
83 shall appoint one member.
84 (b)(1) Appointees to the commission shall be citizens
Page 3

(b)(1) Appointees to the commission shall be citizens
SB128 Engrossed
85 residents of this state and shall be subject to confirmation
86 by the Senate, and upon confirmation, serve for a term of four
87 years. The membership of the commission shall be inclusive and
88 reflect the racial, gender, geographic, urban/rural urban,
89 rural, and economic diversity of the state. The commission
90 shall annually report to the Legislature by the second
91 legislative day of each regular session the extent to which
92 the commission has complied with the diversity provisions of
93 this subsection subdivision. In the event of the death or
94 resignation of any member of the commission, a successor shall
95 be appointed by the original appointing authority and the
96 successor appointed to the vacancy shall serve for the
97 remainder of the unexpired term. The members shall elect from
98 their membership a chair and a vice chair at an organizational
99 meeting held no later than 30 days after appointments to the
100 commission are confirmed.
101 (2) All appointees shall serve their appointed terms
102 unless the Senate elects to consider and then rejects an
103 appointment. The entire Senate or the Senate Committee on
104 Confirmations may elect to consider an appointment. If an
105 appointment is rejected by the Senate Committee on
106 Confirmations, the rejection shall be considered a rejection
107 by the entire Senate.
108 (c) Members of the commission shall receive no salaries
109 but may be reimbursed for actual and necessary expenditures
110 incurred in the performance of their official duties pursuant
111 to Article 2 of Chapter 7 of Title 36. Expenses of the
112 commission are to be paid from funds available to the
Page 4

